materials_text: {"blocks":[{"key":"63fvv","text":"Information sources","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"t69s","text":"http://www.stereology.info/number/","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":0,"length":34}],"data":{}},{"key":"eo3gf","text":"http://www.stereology.info/the-optical-fractionator/","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":1,"offset":0,"length":52}],"data":{}},{"key":"41ugj","text":"http://www.stereology.info/the-fractionator-principle/","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":2,"offset":0,"length":54}],"data":{}},{"key":"8lk6g","text":"The Stereo Investigator user guide is within software help menu.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"35brg","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"64eme","text":"Rules of thumb:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dubu7","text":"● You should aim to count roughly 200 cells to get a CE of \u003c0.1 (even better if \u003c0.05; but","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9s7fb","text":"much less than 0.05 means that you’re probably doing more work than you need to).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fdpkj","text":"● You should use about 10 sections covering the entire structure of interest (therefore, you","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6885u","text":"are looking to count about 20 cells per section). For each brain, the choice of the first","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4fekt","text":"section should be random with respect to the structure of interest; thereafter the section","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cmi1h","text":"interval should be constant (ie. if taking every third section from serial sections, the","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9lacq","text":"choice of whether the first section is section 1, 2, or 3 should be random, but then you","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"dh709","text":"would take sections 1, 4, 7…, or 2, 5, 8…, or 3, 6, 9… respectively).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9tmod","text":"● Counting frame size should give an average of 3–4 cells counted per frame. This may","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"66gmo","text":"appear to suggest that a grid size that gives 5–7 counting frames per section would be","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3f5rp","text":"ideal; but in practice more counting frames per section are needed (~10), this is because","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9p9p7","text":"many counting frames will fall at the edge of the structure and will have few or no cells to","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3ghtv","text":"count. The CE calculation is complex, but more smaller counting frames tends to give a","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6e4in","text":"lower CE than fewer larger counting frames.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5h70","text":"● The image acquisition workflow will only image one field of view per counting frame. This","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8soot","text":"means that counting frame size is limited by the field of view. At 100×, 50 × 50 μm is","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"eus3s","text":"about as large as the counting frame can be. At 40×, sizes up to 100 × 100 μm are OK.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"82nib","text":"If the counting frame is too large imaging will proceed as normal, but you may get odd","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"31bsc","text":"behaviour in the optical fractionator workflow.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"e6d0q","text":"● The guard zone should take you beyond fluctuations in the slice surface. Ideally it would","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8igse","text":"be at least one cell diameter (if counting cells), but for immunostained tissue a guard","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"hvl6","text":"zone this thick is unlikely to ever be practical.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"792r1","text":"● The probe thickness would ideally be much greater than one cell diameter (if counting","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bfvap","text":"cells), but again for immunostained tissue this is unlikely to ever be practical.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3dt11","text":"● For immunostained tissue, top guard zone + probe thickness should be less than","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"odmp","text":"antibody penetration depth. Obviously this has to take precedence over the previous two","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fb7g3","text":"rules (you can’t count cells that you can’t see).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"flg75","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4edcu","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"5560A771352111ED98330A58A9FEAC02","url":"http://www.stereology.info/number"}},"1":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"5560A7AF352111ED98330A58A9FEAC02","url":"http://www.stereology.info/the-optical-fractionator"}},"2":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"5560A7D5352111ED98330A58A9FEAC02","url":"http://www.stereology.info/the-fractionator-principle"}}}}

They will","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"926b4","text":"be much the same if imaging in two or three channels, but will have to set up multi-channel","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5316s","text":"imaging first. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4pm1k","text":"To minimize bleaching turn the LED off as often as possible during the workflow.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ernir","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"et05t","text":"It is possible to place two slides on the stage, set up all the structure outlines first and then do","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"ajhjs","text":"the imaging in a single step. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"rogn","text":"This doesn’t save much time and increases the chance of an error","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3vjd3","text":"(which, almost always, means starting over), so these instructions are for drawing and imaging","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2lalh","text":"the sections one at a time.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"afr1k","text":"Turn on stage and LED before the computer.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"lmcm","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5qonb","text":"Click ‘Live image’ (for some reason it won’t let you start the workflow until you have","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"8da0r","text":"done this) then go to ‘Acquisition\u003eAcquire SRS Image Stack Workflow’","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"2qhia","text":"Enter sampling parameters, serial section information. If loading existing parameters, do","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9g05t","text":"this first.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"cc85j","text":"Move stage to first section. Click ‘Next Step’. Draw structure outline. Right-click and select ‘close contour’ when done. ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1hvd2","text":"Click ‘Next Step’. Draw structure outline. Right-click and select ‘close contour’ when done. If","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cg4gv","text":"you are interested in this estimate it is worth spending some time on your outlines.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3lipi","text":"However, the math for the optical fractionator does not use this volume estimate , so if","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4ma2d","text":"you are not interested in this volume estimate then the outline is just used to delineate","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7itcc","text":"the area of interest for counting: if your stain marks cells that you are not going to be","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"9dqhf","text":"counting ideally all cells to be counted should be within the outline and all cells not to be","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"3qje1","text":"counted should be outwith the outline.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"50e0r","text":"It’s often useful to check the accuracy of your structure outline at 20×. Move to 20× lens","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4g6re","text":"(and change to 20× in Stereo Investigator) and focus to the top of the slice, then focus","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"4mour","text":"10 to 15 um into the slice. Use ‘Go to’ in macro view or ‘joy track’ mode to move around","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"flqkt","text":"your outline checking it. {"blocks":[{"key":"7gv8b","text":"Click the ‘+’ next to ‘Section 1’ in the Regions of Interest list (left of the screen)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"food3","text":"Click the ‘+’ next to ‘User Line 1’ (or whatever line you used to draw your outlines)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9btn9","text":"Click on ‘Acquired Stacks’. Click the ‘Start Counting’ button (blue arrowhead).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6i0ij","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"9m4sl","text":"Focus with ‘page up’ and ‘page down’ keys to top of section \u0026 click ‘OK’. Click ‘Do Not Measure’","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
{"blocks":[{"key":"dpge3","text":"At left of screen choose a marker (I like marker 10)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"4qnia","text":"Click zoom out in macro view and then zoom in on to your outline (this helps when a","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"70g5","text":"counting frame falls on the edge of an outline to determine what is inside and outside of","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"97b0r","text":"the outline)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"3bliu","text":"Focus down through tissue clicking on cells as they come into focus, but only if they do","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7lvch","text":"so within the probe thickness (the counting frame will be yellow above and below","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"aj5m","text":"counting depth), and only if they are within the outline and within the counting frame. The","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"fvvjr","text":"counting frame includes all cells that touch the green lines, but does not include any that","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"7acm3","text":"touch the red lines (see http://www.stereology.info/counting-rules/ ).","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[{"key":0,"offset":25,"length":42}],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{"0":{"type":"link","mutability":"MUTABLE","data":{"guid":"2A2991EE352411ED98330A58A9FEAC02","url":"http://www.stereology.info/counting-rules"}}}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"a10um","text":"You can improve contrast if needed using the ‘Image Adjustment’ histogram at the top","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"1g9pp","text":"right of the screen (click inside of it to see the histogram)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"5ota3","text":"Continue until all sites on the section have been visited (A ‘Run Completed’ message","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"279ij","text":"box appears)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"54d6g","text":"Select ‘Acquired Stacks’ from next section, and click the blue run button","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7q8ee","text":"Repeat until all sections are counted, then click ‘I’m finished counting’.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"7ca23","text":"For NeuN labelled mouse STN cell nuclei (coronal sections at 70 μm) try:","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"379p8","text":"● Section interval: 1 (at 70 μm there will only be ~8 sections in total)","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"bqasp","text":"● Grid size: 150 × 150 μm","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"2iln1","text":"● Counting frame size: 50 × 50 μm","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"37fgj","text":"● Upper guard zone thickness: 2 μm","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cldkl","text":"● Probe thickness: 8 μm","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"6dk7l","text":"● Image 3 μm above and 8 μm below probe and guard zone","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"cs6p0","text":"For FVB mouse STN these parameters gave: count = ~11000 cells (CE = ~0.08), volume =","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5g1in","text":"~0.09 mm 3 , density = ~121000 cells per mm 3 .","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
